segments.text: Good morning.
This is April 6, 1985.
We are in the living room of Bob Cornish, and I am Bob Cornish.
And I'm interviewing Robert Ashcroft from San Antonio this morning.
Bob has been a longtime activist in planning matters in San Antonio.

And Bob, I'd like to start out first with going back to the origins of San Antonio briefly and describing the influence of the Spanish Law of the Indies on San Antonio and what remains of it at the present time.
Well, I think that we've got to recognize with San Antonio early 18th century that
It was a Spanish colonial settlement.
San Antonio was also significant because it had all three of the Spanish types of settlement.
It had the religious, the military, and the civil.
And all of those had a great deal of influence on San Antonio.
Of course, the first was the religious with the missions, and five of which still exist in various states of
of restoration and repair.
The Presidia, which was the first military settlement, is at the heart of downtown.
The original square is where City Hall is today, and that dates from about 1730 or 1731.
And then about, I guess a decade or so later,
the Pueblo, the first civil settlement, which was the Canary Islanders, was the next plaza to the east, which today is where the courthouse is, and that's known as Main Plaza.
And a lot's been written about the significance of those early planned settlements on San Antonio, and they still maintain an influence today, both in terms of
the street system and the system of plazas and squares and open spaces downtown, as well as the influence of the missions on later planning.
For example, the whole effort to deal with the San Antonio River corridor that reemerged in the 1960s and the river walk at an earlier period of time.
And as I said, people like reps.
And others have documented extensively the plans of those settlements and their influence, not only on San Antonio's development over a period of time, but their influence on American planning.
So the early plans were influenced by the Spanish and the Canary Islanders.
Let's move ahead to the introduction of formal professional planning into San Antonio.
OK. Let me just say as kind of a transition thing,
What we're talking about with respect to the Spanish and their formal plans dates from the early 18th century.
And if one looks at the rest of the 18th century and most all of the 19th century, there was very little formal city planning being undertaken in San Antonio.
I think it's interesting to note that

toward the latter half of the 19th century, post-Civil War period, particularly after 1880, that we started seeing put in place in San Antonio some of those elements that would later affect some of the planning.
In other words, we saw the first efforts to do large-scale development.
Communities like Alamo Heights and then the area along
around what is today known as Woodlawn Lake, which was then known as West End Lake.
These were fairly large scale planned developments.
And I think Alamo Heights as a community is particularly interesting in terms of its street pattern.
It's kind of a curvilinear street pattern, which is very unusual for that period of time in San Antonio.
And in fact, it's unusual for San Antonio until relatively recently because
San Antonio grew by the use of just adding grids, the gridiron street pattern, and it wasn't necessarily just a continuation.
One person that needs to be talked to, and he's got a great set of graphics that depict the development of San Antonio's gridiron street pattern over a period of
of 150 years is a San Antonio architect by the name of Alex Caragon, C-A-R-A-G-O-N-N-E, and he's with Caragon Reyna.
And Alex developed a set of maps that showed how San Antonio evolved with this gridiron street pattern.
Getting back to my point, we saw developers for the first time, we saw the street
railway system initially being an ox drawn, the first line, an ox drawn system, the first line extending from in front of the Alamo on Alamo Plaza up to San Pedro Park.
And then later the electric companies came in and all of these had a substantial influence on how
the community grew over a period of time.
But up until really the 1920s, there was no formal city planning in San Antonio.
It was all being done sort of incrementally by the private sector.
And it's not until the very late 1920s that we see for the first time an attempt on the part of the local government
to do some what we recognize today as community or city planning.
What caused the city to move in the direction of conscious city planning?
Was there any event or series of events that indicated that the city should, in fact, have citywide planning?
Well, I'm not sure that we could
I'm not sure we could or anyone could identify a specific event or reason for the city consciously initiating a planning effort.
I think probably, like most communities, San Antonio faced a lot of problems in terms of very rapid growth.
What you've got to realize is that San Antonio's growth rate
per decade, if you look at, say, from the 1880s to the 1920s and 1930s, San Antonio literally went from a small frontier settlement to the largest metropolitan area in Texas.
And it grew from 10,000 people to well over a quarter of a million people.
Its growth rate per decade averaged 75% to 80%.
So it was almost doubling in size each 10-year period of time.
The cumulative effects of that growth over a period of time, particularly with the introduction of the automobile

substantial increase in population I think led a lot of citizens and particularly some of the public officials to the point where they decided that it was important that a comprehensive look be made of the city and to see if there was anything consciously that the city could do to better deal with its growth and I think that this is true of most cities and it's true of
Each period of time that San Antonio got serious about planning, and it wasn't just in the late 1920s, the same thing happened in the 1970s.
It was in reaction to growth or growth issues.
So I don't think it was a single event.
I think it was just the cumulative effect of a lot of these things.
Did the railroads have much effect on the growth of San Antonio in its early years?
That would be right.
before the Civil War and immediately after.
I guess the railroads did to the extent that the railroads made San Antonio more accessible to the outside world.
Over a period of about 30 or 40 years, San Antonio became a major
terminus point for, I think, four major railroads.
And there were four major railroad stations in San Antonio.
So I think that had an effect on just the growth.
I'm not sure how much effect it had in terms of development patterns, per se.
I think that the intra-urban railway system, particularly
the street railway system was much more significant to San Antonio in that frequently the land developer who bought several hundred acres on the outskirts of the city actually started
a street railway system just to provide the access to the development so that he could sell lots.
And in fact, what someone should do, Ann Morial Watson, who is currently the executive director of the San Antonio Conservation Society, wrote her master's thesis at Trinity University
on a look at the street railway system in San Antonio and its contributions to the development of San Antonio.
And I think that's a paper that if someone wants to get into this area, the detail needs to be looked at.
So I think the local railways as opposed to the inter-urban railways had much more of an effect on San Antonio.
In terms of its pattern.
In terms of its development pattern.
In terms of numbers, probably the railroads had quite an effect, I would think.
Just in assisting growth.
Right.
Okay.
Bob, when was the first legislative authorization of a comprehensive plan in San Antonio?
Well, the first formal
authorization came with our current charter.
And let me explain the background of that a little bit because it is rather significant.
In the very early 1950s, late 1940s, early 1950s, there was a substantial reaction among the progressive element in San Antonio about the correct
corruption in municipal government.
And it was a typical reform type of movement.
And San Antonio had had a commissioned form of government dating back to about the 19- somewhere in the first decade of the 20th century.
They established a commissioned form of government and
had that for a period of almost 40 years.
It was perceived as very corrupt.
A group of citizens got together and drew up a charter for a council manager form of government, feeling that the council manager form of government was the best system
that minimize political influence.
The city would be run by a professional city manager, and the city council, although elected, would basically just set policy and not be involved in the day-to-day operation of government.
And that involvement in the day-to-day operation of government was the thing that really bothered people.
So in late 1951, the charter was drawn up,
It was approved by the voters in very early 1952, I think January 1952, and the council manager for government came to San Antonio.
Now, the significant thing about the charter, in addition to its form of government, is Article 9.
In Article 9 of the city charter, established for the first time the planning function in San Antonio.
And it did it in a very...
substantial in explicit way.
State statute makes no provision in Texas for the planning function of the municipal corporation.
There's no mandated planning in Texas
But the city charter, Article 9 in San Antonio, mandates planning.
And it does so by, first of all, saying that the city shall have a master plan.
It's not permissive.
It's mandatory.
That section of the article of the charter also creates the planning commission.
It creates the planning department.
It specifies...
to a certain extent, and this is probably its greatest weakness, what is meant by a master plan.
And there's only one sentence in there that explains what a master plan should be.
But there's an entire section in there significantly explaining the legal effect of the master plan.
So that once a plan is adopted in San Antonio, the plan has a substantial legal effect.

and as I said, the plan is mandated there, so San Antonio's formal, official, legislative planning beginnings really date from January of 1952 with the start of the San Antonio Charter and particularly Article 9 of that charter.
That's interesting that there was such a late start in San Antonio.
Most cities

got planning underway in the 1910s or the 1920s with the standard acts and with starting with the standard zoning act and then of course the standard city planning enabling act after that and most states patterned their state enabling legislation after the standard acts which
of course, has troubled United States planning to this day because they started out first with zoning and then went to planning after that.
But maybe... Well, let me respond to that.
First of all, the question was, when was San Antonio officially...
When did San Antonio officially recognize planning their mandate?
And that was the date, January 1952.

That is not to say, A, that the city of San Antonio wasn't engaged in certain types of planning activities prior to that time, and it did, San Antonio had adopted zoning in November of 1938, so it had zoning prior to planning.
And some semblance of subdivision regulations, although
The formal modern subdivision regulations in San Antonio really date from about 1958, although there were some semblances of those prior to that time.
And some planning efforts that predated the 1952 thing, but the official thing started in 1952.
What were the pre-official efforts in planning?
Well, the major one
Well, there were two.
The first one was an attempt, and I started talking about this earlier, in the late 1920s to do a plan for the city of San Antonio.
And the city appointed about, I guess, 50 or so members to a city plan commission.
There were a committee, I guess it was called.
There were 56 citizens on it.
And in October of 1929, the city, through this committee, contracted with Harlan Bartholomew and Associates out of St. Louis to work with the city to draw up a master plan for the city.
The effort took
four years and part of that was because of the nature of the committee.
There were various subcommittees that worked with the consultant in different areas.
Part of it was also the lingering effect of the depression.
The city actually ran out of money at one point in time and broke off its relationship with Bartholomew and had not something been done, San Antonio would never have had that plan finished.
what happened was some private citizens that were able to keep the effort going until the city had some additional funds.
So the plan, Bartholomew finished the plan and delivered it to the city in March of 1933, and the city commission officially approved that plan.
The plan itself
was kind of an interesting document.
First of all, it dealt largely with just the 36 square miles that was within the corporate limits at that time.
San Antonio, when it became a legal entity during the Republic of Texas period, was originally charted as a 36 square mile area.
Those boundaries did not change at all for over 100 years.
It wasn't until 1940 when
when San Antonio did its first annexation of Los Angeles Heights, that those boundaries changed.
So Bartholomew, in doing his planning in the early 1930s, just dealt basically with the 36 square mile area.
So if you look at, he did produce a single plan graphic and a document.
And the plan graphic is really kind of a fascinating depiction of a lot of his ideas.
related, most of his ideas related to open space, to parks, to boulevards connecting things, and those types of things which were very popular in those days.
Yeah, the typical city beautiful plan.
Yes, yes.
Is a copy available?
Yes, I am in the process.
Now, there is only one copy available of the original colored graphic.
I know where that is.
I am
having reproduced copies of that and written some high quality reproductions.
That could be available for you.
That could be, yes, and that can and will be available.
And then there is a document that I think there were probably only four or five original copies of
the report that Bartholomew submitted with the plan.
And they were kind of interesting to see in there.
Apparently they were just typewritten and they were carbon copies.
And there is a bound volume of that that the city planning department has.
But they do not have the graphic.
The graphic is in private hands.
Who has that?
I don't want to disclose the name.
So, but I'm making arrangements to have that regrouped.
And it's kind of an amazing, an amazing document.

As we'll see, hopefully, as we discuss later, a plan done by the, a plan graphic done by the city in the 1960s is also kind of an amazing thing to look at and to study and to see how well the planner did a job of
both anticipating how the city might grow and coming up with some solutions to the problems that the city was facing.
But the point is that in March of 33, the Bartholomew plan was adopted by the city commission.
Not really much happened in terms of implementing that plan at all.
Now normally, on that point, Bartholomew, whenever he contracted with a city,
would insist on leaving one of his senior staff planners there to implement the plan, such as in Corpus Christi and or El Paso.
But that doesn't seem to have happened in San Antonio.
Well, yes.
And the reason that probably didn't happen is because the governmental structure at that time had no provision for staff.
In other words, in 1933,
And in fact, up until the charter in 1952, there was no formal planning staff in the city.
So one had to look at the city engineer or someone like that.
And I think the real problem with the Bartholomew plan was the lack of structure and the lack of mechanisms to implement it.
I think one could, and this is getting out on a limb, but one could probably say that

that the adoption of the zoning ordinance in 1938, if one looked at the zoning districts that were proposed, and I think there were 13 original zoning districts, and went back and related those to some of the things in the Bartholomew plan, that the people that probably drew up the first zoning district map did refer to Bartholomew's plan.
And that's an assumption on my part.
But other than that...
There seems to be a relationship.
There seems to be some relationship there.

But other than that, there really was not much of an effort, a formal effort, either through subdivision regulations, which were largely non-existent at that time, through capital improvement programs of any type, which also there weren't many significant...
at that time, nor through zoning, nor through city staff to implement it.
So, whereas Bartholomew, as you said, in other cities may have had the opportunity to put one of his persons in there, that just didn't occur.
The other thing that's significant here is that, is that that plan came to the city
at probably the worst time financially, and that's during the Depression.
The city of San Antonio just had real problems providing basic services.
And as I mentioned earlier, that it was only through the efforts of the private sector that the plan even got finished.
If it was up to the city government, that plan probably would never have been finished.
Speaking of that Depression era, San Antonio benefited quite a bit
The Roosevelt administration, WPA and so forth, could you comment a bit about the public works administration and what they did to improve San Antonio?
Well, yeah, most of that happened at the end of the 1930s into the 1940s, but
That was probably the start of the whole era of project planning in San Antonio, which in my opinion has been a much stronger effort than comprehensive planning.
Project planning, I mean, local government is involved, but rather than focusing on the entire city or an entire area, it dealt with a project.
or a function.
The first substantial effort was the restoration of the La Vita area, which occurred, that project started in the late 1930s under Maury Maverick, who was mayor at that time.
And then that was followed by the other major significant project, which was the Riverwalk, the Paseo Del Rio.
Most of that construction occurred during the early 1940s.
And those two projects, I think, really set the tone for project planning in San Antonio.
And although they've come to have very significant consequences for the city of San Antonio, initially they didn't have a particular...
effect in terms of creating a lot of additional development.
The river walk, Upsit Doria, really sat for decades without anything being done.
La Vita worked a little bit better than the river, but both of those were very early examples of something.
And there were other projects, those were not the only two, but those were the two outstanding
The WPA and the CCC and others accomplished literally dozens of projects in San Antonio.
And also significantly, there was a lot of effort in the area of documentation.
A lot of measured drawings were done during that period of time.
Some guides were done.
I've got copies of guides for both the river
and lobby each of it were done by the WPA, pointing out how this whole thing turned out.
Well, my understanding is that the Riverwalk situation came about largely because something had to be done about blood control.
Correct.
And the Los Olmos Dam was built to control the San Antonio River after the downtown had been flooded to a depth of six feet, I believe in 1925.
Yeah.
Well, the dam came much later.
Correct.
There was a devastating, well, there were a series of floods that occurred in the first couple of decades of the 20th century.
I think it was 1923.
I could be wrong on that date.
It could have been 25.
There was a major flood in downtown San Antonio, largely because of
If one looks at the surface hydrology of San Antonio, above the headwaters of the San Antonio River in the Bracken Ridge Park area, above that is the whole Olmos River Basin.
And what would happen is you would have huge rainfalls up there and that would just come right down through the middle of downtown.
The reaction to that was
let's do something about the river.
Apparently the downtown merchants insisted that the city council do something.
Yeah, and basically it was a, one of the proposals was a flood control proposal which would basically have put the river underground.
And the reaction to that is the famous story about

the birth of the San Antonio Conservation Society in the 1920s and Miss Emily Edwards who was its first president was the woman who prevailed upon the city commission at that time to quote unquote save the river in the famous puppet show and all that's been documented and that led then to the city holding off on doing something about
that stringent flood control measure and that allowed the opportunity with Robert Huggman's idea later to come up with the Paseo Del Rio.
Without the Conservation Society's initial effort, there wouldn't have been anything for Huggman to plan.
He had no official
role with the city.
I think it was mostly with the conservation group.
Well, Hugman's effort was kind of a separate effort from the society.
Hugman worked directly with some downtown property owners, particularly Jack White, who at that time owned what was then the Plaza Hotel.
